entials or fitting a particular mold. Should we address it? Absolutely. The evidence is compelling that stereotype threat leads to real performance gaps that have nothing to do with actual ability. When talented individuals underperform or leave STEM fields because the environment constantly signals they don't fit, we lose valuable perspectives and contributions. In my work as a UX designer, I've learned that small design choices dramatically impact user confidence and success. The same principle applies here. How do we address it? I think the solution requires intentional environmental design. First, we need representation at all levels so that students and professionals see people like themselves succeeding. Second, framing matters enormously. Instead of treating diversity as remedial, we should emphasize that diverse perspectives strengthen problem-solving, which research supports. Third, creating evaluation contexts that reduce identity salience helps. For instance, presenting tests as learning tools rather than ability measures can reduce threat. Fourth, fostering growth mindset cultures where struggle is normalized rather than seen as evidence of inadequacy makes spaces safer. In Milan's tech scene, I've noticed companies beginning to recognize these issues, though implementation remains inconsistent. The curious part of me wants to see more systematic approaches grounded in research rather than superficial diversity initiatives. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about lowering standards but about removing artificial barriers that prevent people from showing their true capabilities.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 22-year-old UX designer with a master's degree, indicating technical knowledge and education in human-centered design principles. His curious psychological feature suggests he would approach this topic with intellectual interest. His diverse parental educational background (PhD vs no formal education) provides personal insight into educationa